[
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What aspect of language does Speech Act Theory emphasize?",
      "Back": "The <strong>pragmatics</strong> of language (the intended meaning or goal of an utterance), as opposed to just syntax and semantics."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "Speech act theory was introduced by {{c1::John L. Austin}} in his 1962 book, \"{{c2::How to Do Things with Words}}\"."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the core idea of John L. Austin's speech act theory?",
      "Back": "That what we say can change the world in a way similar to physical actions.<br>Examples: Declaring war, pronouncing a couple married, a judge deciding a legal case."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In speech act theory, what is the <strong>locution</strong>?",
      "Back": "The physical act of saying something; the utterance of sounds or words."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In speech act theory, what is the <strong>illocution</strong>?",
      "Back": "The associated act of showing an intention or goal, such as stating, questioning, commanding, or promising."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In speech act theory, what is the <strong>perlocution</strong>?",
      "Back": "The resulting action or event caused by the speech act, such as a change in belief, an answer, or a physical action."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "According to John Searle, a {{c1::representative}} speech act is aimed at informing. <br>Example: 'I made tea'."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "According to John Searle, a {{c1::directive}} speech act is aimed at the hearer doing something. <br>Example: 'Please make the tea'."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "According to John Searle, a {{c1::commissive}} speech act is aimed at a commitment of the speaker. <br>Example: 'I promise to make tea'."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "According to John Searle, an {{c1::expressive}} speech act is aimed at expressing a mental state. <br>Example: 'I like this tea!'"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "According to John Searle, a {{c1::declarative}} speech act is aimed at a change of the world. <br>Example: 'I declare you man and wife'."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What are the two main components of a speech act?",
      "Back": "1. A <strong>performative verb</strong> (e.g., request, inform, promise)<br>2. <strong>Propositional content</strong> (e.g., \"the door is closed\")"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "How did Cohen & Perrault (1979) define speech acts?",
      "Back": "Using logic, in terms of <strong>preconditions</strong> and <strong>postconditions</strong> (or rational effects)."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the key difference between defining a speech act and a physical action using pre/postconditions?",
      "Back": "A speech act is defined by an <strong>intention or goal</strong>, not by an actual outcome."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the rational effect (postcondition) of a `request(s, h, a)` speech act?",
      "Back": "The hearer (h) believes that the speaker (s) believes that the speaker wants action (a) to be performed.<br>Formal: `h believes (s believes (s want a))`"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What does FIPA stand for in the context of agent communication?",
      "Back": "Foundation for Intelligent Physical Agents."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "FIPA"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "Describe the basic flow of the FIPA-Propose-Protocol.",
      "Back": "1. The <strong>Initiator</strong> sends a `propose` message to the <strong>Participant</strong>.<br>2. The <strong>Participant</strong> responds with either `accept-proposal` or `reject-proposal`."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Protocols",
      "FIPA"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "The Contract Net Protocol is a formalized protocol for task sharing with five phases:<br>1. {{c1::Recognition}}<br>2. {{c2::Announcement}}<br>3. {{c3::Bidding}}<br>4. {{c4::Awarding}}<br>5. {{c5::Expediting}}"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Protocols"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In the FIPA-ContractNet-Protocol, what message does the Initiator send to start the process?",
      "Back": "A `cfp` (call for proposals) message."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Protocols",
      "FIPA"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the primary goal of an auction?",
      "Back": "To allocate goods, typically scarce resources, to agents."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In auction theory, what does it mean for an allocation to be 'efficient'?",
      "Back": "The resources are allocated to the agents that value them the most."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What are the three main types of value a good can have in an auction?",
      "Back": "1. <strong>Private value</strong> (each bidder has their own valuation)<br>2. <strong>Public/common value</strong> (the good has the same value for everyone, but it's unknown)<br>3. <strong>Correlated value</strong> (bidders' valuations are related)"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What are the four main types of auctions discussed?",
      "Back": "1. English auctions<br>2. Dutch auctions<br>3. First-price sealed-bid auctions<br>4. Vickrey auctions"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "An English auction is a {{c1::first-price}}, {{c2::open-cry}}, {{c3::ascending}} auction."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the dominant strategy for a bidder in an English auction?",
      "Back": "Successively bid a small amount more than the current highest bid until the price reaches the agent’s own valuation, then withdraw."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "A Dutch auction is an {{c1::open-cry}}, {{c2::descending}} auction."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "A First-Price Sealed-Bid auction is a {{c1::one-shot}} auction where the winner pays the price of the {{c2::highest bid}}."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "Why is there an incentive to bid less than your true valuation in a first-price sealed-bid auction?",
      "Back": "Because the winner pays their own high bid, but they could have potentially won by bidding just slightly more than the second-highest bid. Bidding lower reduces the risk of overpaying."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Cloze",
    "fields": {
      "Text": "A Vickrey auction is a {{c1::second-price}}, {{c2::sealed-bid}} auction."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In a Vickrey auction, how is the winner determined and what price do they pay?",
      "Back": "The agent with the <strong>highest bid</strong> wins, but they pay the price of the <strong>second-highest bid</strong>."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the dominant strategy in a Vickrey auction?",
      "Back": "To bid your <strong>true valuation</strong> of the good."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "In auctions, what are 'shills'?",
      "Back": "Secret associates of the seller who bid on the item to artificially drive up the price. This is an issue primarily in English (ascending) auctions."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is 'bidder collusion' in auctions?",
      "Back": "When bidders collaborate to decrease the prices paid, for example, by agreeing that only one of them will bid and they will share the item later."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What is the 'winner's curse' in auctions?",
      "Back": "The phenomenon where the winner of an auction may have overvalued the good, since their valuation was higher than everyone else's. They may have paid more than the good's true worth."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Auctions"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "According to Walton and Krabbe, what is a <strong>Persuasion</strong> dialogue?",
      "Back": "<strong>Initial Situation:</strong> Conflict of Opinions<br><strong>Participant's Goal:</strong> Persuade Other Party<br><strong>Goal of Dialogue:</strong> Resolve or Clarify Issue"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "According to Walton and Krabbe, what is an <strong>Inquiry</strong> dialogue?",
      "Back": "<strong>Initial Situation:</strong> Need to Have Proof<br><strong>Participant's Goal:</strong> Find and Verify Evidence<br><strong>Goal of Dialogue:</strong> Prove (Disprove) Hypothesis"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "According to Walton and Krabbe, what is a <strong>Negotiation</strong> dialogue?",
      "Back": "<strong>Initial Situation:</strong> Conflict of Interests<br><strong>Participant's Goal:</strong> Get What You Most Want<br><strong>Goal of Dialogue:</strong> Reasonable Settlement Both Can Live With"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "According to Walton and Krabbe, what is an <strong>Information-Seeking</strong> dialogue?",
      "Back": "<strong>Initial Situation:</strong> Need Information<br><strong>Participant's Goal:</strong> Acquire or Give Information<br><strong>Goal of Dialogue:</strong> Exchange Information"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "According to Walton and Krabbe, what is a <strong>Deliberation</strong> dialogue?",
      "Back": "<strong>Initial Situation:</strong> Dilemma or Practical Choice<br><strong>Participant's Goal:</strong> Co-ordinate Goals and Actions<br><strong>Goal of Dialogue:</strong> Decide Best Available Course of Action"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "According to Walton and Krabbe, what is an <strong>Eristic</strong> dialogue?",
      "Back": "<strong>Initial Situation:</strong> Personal Conflict<br><strong>Participant's Goal:</strong> Verbally Hit Out at Opponent<br><strong>Goal of Dialogue:</strong> Reveal Deeper Basis of Conflict"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What are four basic speech acts used in argumentation dialogue?",
      "Back": "1. <strong>Claim φ</strong> (make an assertion)<br>2. <strong>Argue φ so ψ</strong> (give a reason)<br>3. <strong>Challenge why φ?</strong> (ask for a reason)<br>4. <strong>Retract φ</strong> (withdraw a claim)"
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue",
      "SpeechActs"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "What was the goal of Luc Steels' \"Talking Heads\" experiment?",
      "Back": "To study dialogue-based language development, where software agents could autonomously develop a shared language (lexicon and grammar) through interaction."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  },
  {
    "model_name": "Basic",
    "fields": {
      "Front": "Briefly describe the \"guessing game\" used in the Talking Heads experiment.",
      "Back": "1. A speaker (S) chooses a topic (object in a scene) and tries to describe it with a signal (word).<br>2. A hearer (H) points its camera at the object it thinks is being described.<br>3. The speaker provides feedback (success/failure), helping the agents to converge on a shared meaning for signals."
    },
    "tags": [
      "KAS",
      "Communication",
      "Dialogue"
    ]
  }
]
